<p><strong>Social Psychology Goals in Interaction, 5th Edition: Key Concepts and Questions</strong></p>
<p><strong>1. Understanding the Basics</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>What are the major goals of social psychology?</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>To understand how people think, feel, and behave in social situations</li>
<li>To identify the factors that influence social behavior</li>
<li>To apply this knowledge to solve social problems</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>What is the difference between social and non-social behavior?</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Social behavior is influenced by the presence of others</li>
<li>Non-social behavior is not influenced by the presence of others</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>2. The Self in Social Interaction</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>How does our self-concept influence our behavior?</strong><ul>
<li>Our self-concept is our beliefs about who we are</li>
<li>It affects our expectations, goals, and interpretations of events</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>How do we present ourselves to others?</strong><ul>
<li>We manage our self-presentation in order to create a desired impression</li>
<li>This involves choosing our appearance, behavior, and communication style</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>3. Social Perception and Cognition</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>How do we form impressions of others?</strong><ul>
<li>We use schemas, stereotypes, and heuristics to make quick judgments</li>
<li>These judgments can be biased and inaccurate</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>How do we attribute causes to behavior?</strong><ul>
<li>We use the fundamental attribution error to overestimate the influence of dispositional factors and underestimate the influence of situational factors</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>4. Social Influence</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>How can others influence our thoughts, feelings, and behaviors?</strong><ul>
<li>Through conformity, obedience, and persuasion</li>
<li>The extent of influence depends on the source of the influence and the situation</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>How can we resist social influence?</strong><ul>
<li>By being aware of our own biases and limitations</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>5. Social Relationships</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>What are the different types of social relationships?</strong><ul>
<li>Close relationships, friendships, romantic relationships, and group relationships</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>How do we develop and maintain social relationships?</strong><ul>
<li>Through social exchange, self-disclosure, and social support</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>